# Design system quality

Prevent **demo-quality** UI: inconsistent spacing, random colors, one-off components, and screens that look finished but feel fragile. Enforce **consistent, product-grade** design using existing tokens and shared components.

For product depth vs calm-study tradeoffs, see `.cursor/rules/06-product-ux-benchmark.mdc`. For i18n, a11y basics, and polish checklist, see `.cursor/rules/04-ui-ux-polish.mdc`.

---

## Design principles

- **Clean, learner-first, calm, modern** — the interface supports focus, not spectacle.
- Functionality may be **rich**, but the **first visual impression** must stay **simple** (progressive disclosure beats a wall of controls).
- **Clarity over decoration** — every visual choice should aid scanning, hierarchy, or action.
- **Reusable components over one-off styling** — extend patterns; do not invent a new “card style” per screen.
- **Use existing tokens and components before adding new styles** — new CSS is a last resort after checking the design system.

---

## Layout

- Use a **consistent spacing scale** (existing tokens or shared spacing utilities — no arbitrary pixel soup).
- Prefer **card-based grouping** for learner (and learner-adjacent) content blocks.
- Each **section** should have a clear **title**, **purpose**, and **action area** (what it is, why it matters, what to do next).
- Avoid **nesting too many bordered boxes** — combine or flatten; use spacing and typography to separate instead of frames inside frames.
- Avoid **more than two visual emphasis levels** in one card (e.g. one strong headline + one de-emphasized meta layer; avoid competing bold colors and multiple “hero” treatments).
- **Desktop:** two-column layouts are fine when **list + detail** (or equivalent) are both useful side by side.
- **Mobile:** stack content naturally; keep **primary actions reachable** (thumb zone, sticky footers only when they do not obscure content).

---

## Typography

- **Clear hierarchy:** page/section title → primary content → secondary metadata → helper text.
- Do **not** use too many font sizes in one component — typically title, body, and one smaller line suffice.
- **Japanese text** needs **comfortable line height** for readability; do not squeeze lines to match Latin-only layouts.
- Long explanations must be **scannable** (short paragraphs, bullets where appropriate, clear subheads).

---

## Color and visual style

- Use **existing color tokens** only; do not introduce one-off hex/rgb values for UI chrome.
- **No random accent colors** — meaning (success, warning, link, destructive) comes from the token set.
- Avoid **excessive gradients** and **heavy shadows**; prefer flat or subtle elevation consistent with the rest of the app.
- Use **muted surfaces** for secondary info so primary content stays in focus.
- Use **color to communicate meaning** (state, emphasis, danger), not decoration.

---

## Interaction

- **Primary action** must be visually and structurally obvious.
- **Secondary actions** must not compete with the primary (size, color, placement).
- **Hover, focus, and active** states must exist for interactive elements; keyboard focus must be visible.
- **Disabled** and **loading** states must be unambiguous (no dead clicks, no silent spinners).
- **No surprise autoplay** of audio or video; start only on explicit learner action unless the product spec says otherwise.
- **Respect `prefers-reduced-motion`** when adding or extending motion.

---

## Components

- Prefer existing **Button**, **Card**, **Badge**, **Tabs**, **Accordion**, **Tooltip**, and other primitives already in the codebase.
- **Do not create a new component** if an existing one fits with minor composition or props.
- If a new component is justified, keep it **small, reusable, and typed** — props and variants should be easy to infer from usage.
- Component **API should be clear** (explicit prop names, avoid ambiguous booleans without labels in types/docs).

---

## Quality gate (before finalizing UI)

Self-review:

1. Does it look like a **real product**, not a prototype?
2. Is the **main action obvious within ~3 seconds**?
3. Is the layout **balanced on desktop and mobile**?
4. Are **loading, empty, and error** states handled with helpful, non-technical copy (and i18n keys)?
5. Is **visual density** appropriate for learners (not a dense admin spreadsheet unless the screen is truly admin/analytics)?
6. Are there any **hard-coded user-visible strings**? (Must use message catalogs.)
7. Is **accessibility** acceptable (semantic structure, contrast, touch targets, focus)?

If any answer is weak, fix before shipping the change.
